The `main.tsx` file is the entry point for the React application.

## Purpose

This file is responsible for initializing the React application and rendering the root `App` component into the DOM. It utilizes `React.StrictMode` to enable additional checks and warnings during development.

## Key Exports/Functions

- **`createRoot`**: From `react-dom/client`, this function is used to create a root for the React application, targeting a specific DOM element.
- **`document.getElementById("root")!`**: Selects the HTML element with the ID 'root' where the React application will be mounted. The `!` asserts that the element will not be null.
- **`render`**: The method called on the root object to mount the React component tree into the DOM.
- **`StrictMode`**: A tool for highlighting potential problems in an application. It only activates in development and won't affect the production build.
- **`App`**: The main application component, which is imported from `./App`.

## Usage Example

This file is typically not modified directly after initial setup. It's the core bootstrap logic for the React app. The configuration assumes an `index.html` file exists with a `<div id="root"></div>` element.

```tsx
// This is the content of main.tsx
import { StrictMode } from "react";
import { createRoot } from "react-dom/client";
import "./App.css";
import App from "./App";

createRoot(document.getElementById("root")!).render(
  <StrictMode>
    <App />
  </StrictMode>
);
```
